<dl id="n14070b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14070b">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14070b"> 70(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Kath Debora</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The roots of these tendencies are essentially to be found in Luther. He was ready, in principle, to meet actual and natural life halfway, doing this, moreover, with so complete a <i>naivet&eacute;</i> that there was no hint of a bad conscience&mdash;far less of sin&mdash;about it. As we know, he removed the ban which Gregory VII (1074) had placed upon the marriage of the priesthood, and married <mark>Katherine de Bora</mark> in order to carry his own convictions into practice. <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 54</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
